<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-mode" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Mode</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_8bn3d4ea">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_wa564nyk">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_mzhh1d07">
                        3.0 Statistics and Probability
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_coa48tum">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_f5cf26rp">
                        3.1 Statistics 1
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0yq71cy1">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_3kr1m87l">
                        Determine mean, mode and median of grouped and ungrouped data
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_o172zfha" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_is8j27k7">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_y8e7wtcx" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_n262qrv9">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_x4ploai4" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_1z5lsp6o"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_sup521b8">
                        <p xml:id="auto_s2h5duwt">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that the mode is the value that occurs most frequently in a data set.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_sevmx457">
                        <p xml:id="auto_82kkjti4">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Identify the mode from raw data and frequency distribution tables, including unimodal, bimodal, multimodal, and no-mode cases.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ggqprdiz">
                        <p xml:id="auto_l3kc0q2z">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Use the mode to make practical decisions in real-world situations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_pz4yhjp0">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/statistics-and-probability/statistics-1/mode.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_go9f232l">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/statistics-and-probability/statistics-1/step-by-step-guide_mode.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_qdn3md9k">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_e7rpvoof">15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_es3cgxje">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ymdw08ca">Students work in groups to discover the concept of mode as the most frequently occurring value.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Discussion Prompts</title>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_x1gzaou7"><p xml:id="auto_j92ad4et">Which time appears most often in the votes?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_o92nx5jd"><p xml:id="auto_imhiplbs">How did you count the frequencies?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_17krklao"><p xml:id="auto_r9bxyydz">Why is the most frequent choice a good decision for the class?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hk5rtbxh"><p xml:id="auto_q1jg6nib">What does <q>mode</q> mean in everyday language? How does it connect to statistics?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lyxdwl3h"><p xml:id="auto_usztu2h4">Can there be more than one mode? When would that happen?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_dprce9ad">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_wgyjfnh9">
            <p xml:id="auto_kb5nxst9">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_kl62ie5m">
                Your class is scheduling a favourable revision time. 
                Students voted for their preferred time and the recorded votes are:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_g17zt732">
                Afternoon, Evening, Afternoon, Morning, Afternoon, Evening, Morning, Afternoon, 
                Evening, Morning, morning, Afternoon, Evening, Morning, Afternoon, Evening, 
                Morning, Afternoon, Evening, Morning
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_dj4q7w8f">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_jfjpwm3r">
                    Identify the mode
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_dmi91ip9">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_stsjyjo3">
                    If the class chooses the most preferred time, when will the revision be held?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_v4ix8lga">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_0hl5tpoj">
                    Explain why the mode is important in making this decision.
                </p>
                
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_8vao99d3">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_tcl7711x">
                    If the class had chosen the least preferred time, when would the revision have been held?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_ijm2ofs6">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_y5jz9ikf">
                    Share your work with the class
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_qawykcd2">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_aisn508k">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_wxhm3dgd">10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ps0y2bdb">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_90yx5w9t">To formalize the definition of mode and the four possible cases: unimodal, bimodal, multimodal, and no mode.</p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_tc3pvwop">
        <p xml:id="auto_f9xm0ix3">
            The mode is the value that occurs most frequently in a data set.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_09937hvw">
            A data set may have:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8h5l8vv9">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_dhbeidfl">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zq2ycpah">
                            One mode (unimodal)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_duyz10xi">
                    <p xml:id="auto_0gy5q5gn">
                            Two modes (bimodal)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tqed9zqo">
                    <p xml:id="auto_beu1gbdi">
                            More than two modes (multimodal)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_c7pwgobs">
                    <p xml:id="auto_bmuxi3uz">
                            No mode (if all values occur once)
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o9c4wqns">
            The mode is useful in identifying the most common occurrence in real-life situations.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_f4x2i2i4">
            The mode does not require calculation — it requires counting and comparison.
        </p>
    </insight>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_9dgc4hpy">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_4ubu7k07">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ppseqbnj">15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_thp4p93h">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_kaabkxam">To apply the concept of mode to identify the most frequently occurring values in datasets.</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_7y5jmo4d">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_mdxl023a">Work through examples with learners step by step. Circulate during independent practice and provide assistance where needed.</p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <example xml:id="auto_lys0mbon">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_d6wqco0x">
                The following data set represents the number of goals scored by a football team in 20 matches:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ojpw71da">
                2, 3, 1, 4, 2, 5, 3, 2, 4, 1, 3, 2, 4, 5, 3, 2, 1, 4, 3, 2
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_x9cimjh0">
                Determine the mode of the data set.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_0cgxhcjr">
                To find the mode, we count the frequency of each number of goals scored:
            </p>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell>Number of Goals</cell>
                    <cell>Frequency</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>3</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2</cell>
                    <cell>6</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>3</cell>
                    <cell>5</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>4</cell>
                    <cell>4</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>5</cell>
                    <cell>2</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p xml:id="auto_4vvb6t3d">
                The number of goals that occurs most frequently is 2, which occurs 6 times.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_xya2e58k">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_fdnbzmgg">
                The following data set represents the number of hours spent studying by a group of students in a week:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_etrrc5o6">
                5, 6, 7, 5, 8, 6, 7, 5, 6, 8
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_r2ehaplx">
                Determine the mode of the data set.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_i8bxjksd">
                Using the frequency table, we count the frequency of each number of hours spent studying:
            </p>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell>Hours Studied</cell>
                    <cell>Frequency</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>5</cell>
                    <cell>3</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>6</cell>
                    <cell>3</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>7</cell>
                    <cell>2</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>8</cell>
                    <cell>2</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p xml:id="auto_k805yyrs">
                The number of hours that occurs most frequently is 5 and 6, each occurring 3 times.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_h75pbrcf">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_zln0pfzm">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_9ttqqk8x">To formatively assess individual learner understanding.</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_g3dqgzlb">
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_0ntvpmj5">Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_xt4cypd2">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ov8frwpo">Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.</p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />

     <exercise  label="ex-finding-the-central-tendency-for-ungrouped-data">
        <stack label="stk-finding-the-central-tendency-for-ungrouped-data" source="stack/top/3-0-Statistics-Probability/Statistics-1/3-1-3-Measures-of-Central-Tendency/3-1-3-1-Ungrouped-Data-for-Measures-of-Central-Tendency/Finding-the-central-tendency-for-ungrouped-data.xml" />
    </exercise>
        
    <exercise  label="ex-analysis-of-ungrouped-data-for-kabras-sugar-company">
        <stack label="stk-analysis-of-ungrouped-data-for-kabras-sugar-company" source="stack/top/3-0-Statistics-Probability/Statistics-1/3-1-3-Measures-of-Central-Tendency/3-1-3-1-Ungrouped-Data-for-Measures-of-Central-Tendency/Analysis-of-ungrouped-data-for-kabras-sugar-company.xml" />
    </exercise>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-mode">
        <title>Exercise</title>
        
        
        <exercise xml:id="auto_z6mv9ymq">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ohdy3bwi">
                    The following data set represents the number of pets owned by a group of people:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_pfvqt8oc">
                    0, 1, 2, 3, 1, 0, 2, 4, 1, 3
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_khvd3lua">
                    Determine the mode.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_kvo37wak">
                    The number of pets that occurs most frequently is 1, which occurs 3 times.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_f4frq9t4">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_b3mqq86c">
                The following data set represents the number of books read by a group of students in a month:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_r8l4hs3p">
                2, 3, 1, 4, 2, 5, 3, 2, 4, 1, 3, 2, 4, 5, 3
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_qfx2h7rq">
                Determine the mode.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p xml:id="auto_dz8ma0cm">
                The number of books that occurs most frequently is 2, which occurs 4 times.
            </p>
        </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="auto_c78q1xwx">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_ko3f42ej">
                The shoe sizes of students are:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_a3hetm5x">
                38, 39, 40, 38, 41, 39, 38, 40, 39, 42
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zogoynbv">
                Find the common shoe size among the students.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p xml:id="auto_m06v1m7l">
                The common shoe size among the students is 38 and 39, each occurring 3 times.
            </p>
        </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="auto_yhd9bljp">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_lh0e7rgc">
                The mathematics test scores of Grade 10 students are:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ho4mlcri">
                75, 60, 85, 65, 90, 80, 50, 45, 70, 95
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_78r60il1">
                What is the mode of the test scores?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p xml:id="auto_zz7aiu5p">
                There is no mode since each score appears only once.
            </p>
        </answer>
    </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table xml:id="auto_vvjw1j8p">
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Use tally marks to count frequencies visually. Provide pre-drawn frequency tables to fill in. Use coloured markers to highlight the most frequent value. Start with smaller datasets (5–8 values). Use physical objects (coloured blocks, cards) to represent data. Work in pairs with peer support.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Explore bimodal and multimodal datasets. Compare mode, mean, and median for the same dataset. Investigate when mode is more useful than mean or median. Create their own datasets with specific mode characteristics. Research real-world applications: market research, quality control, fashion industry. Analyse categorical data (favourite colours, preferred subjects) where mode is the only applicable measure.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>
    
    
</subsubsection>